\begin_layout Standard
The continued maintenance of diversity in spite of widespread competition
 has bewildered ecologists, especially for primary producers such as phytoplankt
on that share the same basic resources 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "hutchinson_paradox_1961"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The first solution that has been proposed for the 'paradox of the plankon'
 was the temporal variation of the environment.
 However, inclusion of temporal variability per se in competition models
 is not sufficient for maintaining a realistic diversity 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "fox_intermediate_2013"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Additional mechanisms such as the storage effect 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "chesson_multispecies_1994,ellner_how_2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 or relative nonlinearity of competition 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "chesson_mechanisms_2000,fox_intermediate_2013"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 need to be introduced.
 Richness rarely exceeds a dozen of species in this type of model, except
 when external inputs such as immigration maintain the dynamics 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "jabot_non-random_2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 To our knowledge, the effect of temporal variability on persistence in
 competition models has mostly been tested in theoretical communities of
 2 to 3 species 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "chesson_roles_1997,litchman_competition_2001"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 
