\begin_layout Standard
One of the richest modeled communities that we identified is the model of
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "scranton_coexistence_2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, which is based on temperature variation and different thermal optima for
 each species 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "moisan_modelling_2002"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In this model, the synchronizing effect of the environment and the storage
 effect can maintain 12 phytoplankton-like species on average.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "scranton_coexistence_2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 described daily temperature as a random noise, i.e., independent and identically
 distributed Gaussian random variates over time.
 However, under most latitudes, seasonality drives part of the environmental
 variation: over short timescales, random temporal variations often only
 add noise to a largely deterministic seasonal trend.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Seasonality can indeed strongly affect the dynamics of communities, whether
 it be in models 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "miller_evolutionary_2017,vesipa_impact_2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 or in empirical analyses 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "boyce_environmental_2017,barraquand2018coastal"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 How seasonality affects coexistence, as opposed to a purely randomly fluctuatin
g environment, is therefore a key feature of this paper.
 Our present work can be seen as an attempt to blend 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "scranton_coexistence_2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

's stochastic framework with the periodic environments of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "barabas_community_2012"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, to better represent the mixture of stochastic and deterministic environmental
 forces affecting phytoplankton community dynamics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Niche differences between species, leading to intraspecific interaction
 stronger than interspecific interactions, has recently been confirmed as
 a key mechanism in terrestrial plant communties 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "adler_competition_2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, animal communities 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "mutshinda_what_2009"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, and phytoplanktonic communities 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "barraquand2018coastal"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The interaction between environment variability and niche overlap has been
 investigated by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "abrams_niche_1976"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 but their relative contribution to coexistence was not evaluated.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Niche models have often been opposed to the neutral theory 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "hubbell_unified_2001"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 An intriguing offshoot of the niche vs neutrality debate is the concept
 of `clumpy coexistence' 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "scheffer_self-organized_2006"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, whereby simultaneous influences of both niche and neutral processes create
 several clumps of similar species along a single trait axis.
 Niche differences enable coexistence of multiple clumps 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "chesson_mechanisms_2000"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 while within-clumps coexistence occurs through neutral processes.
 This `emergent neutrality' within groups 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "holt_emergent_2006"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 has been proposed as a unifying concept for niche and neutral theories
 even though the neutrality of such model has been disputed due to hidden
 niches 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "barabas_emergent_2013"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Since then, clumpy coexistence has appeared in theoretical models incorporating
 temporal variations 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "scranton_coexistence_2016,sakavara_lumpy_2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 These models, and the biomass-trait distributions that they output, may
 provide some understanding of multimodal trait patterns 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "dandrea_challenges_2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, we therefore try to establish what are the relative contributions
 to coexistence of the storage effect vs strong self-regulation, in a phytoplank
ton-like theoretical community model.
 We consider both species richness and the distribution of these species.
 This led us to cross different combinations of seasonality in the forcing
 signal, presence of the storage effect or not, and intra- vs interspecific
 competition intensity, in order to disentangle the contributions of all
 these factors to biodiversity maintenance.
\end_layout

